Pixels: Follow-Along Activity
Follow the instructions to create a very simple pixel PAC-MAN!

Pixel Art Examples
Original Mario

All art for video games was once hand-coded, pixel-by-pixel!
Panda
(animated: https://i.imgur.com/ghillV4.gif)

Now, some developers copy this style for their own art
Landscape

Pixel art can be used for almost anything!
Setup

Create a new HTML file named Pixels.html
Add the basic tags to the HTML file - html, head, body
Create a new CSS file named Pixels.css
Link the CSS file in the HTML file using a link tag
href: Pixels.css
rel: stylesheet
type: text/css



Main container

In the HTML file, in the body tag, create a div
Give the div an id attribute: main
This div element will contain the pixels


In the CSS file, create a new ruleset for the main div
Selector: #main
Curly brackets


In the #main ruleset, fill out a few properties:
height: 400px
width: 400px
border: 2px solid black



Pixels.html










Pixels.css
#main {
    width: 400px;
    height: 400px;
    border: 2px solid black;
}

Rows and columns for the grid

In the HTML file, within the main div, create 4 child div elements
Each of these div elements represents one row


Add a class attribute with a value of "horizontal" for each "row" div
Within each of those child div elements, create 4 child div elements
Each of these div elements represents one cell


Add a class attribute with a value of "cell" for each "cell" div


Note: Copy/Paste will make this much faster!




























Styling the cells

In the CSS file, create a new ruleset for each cell
Selector: .cell
Curly brackets


Set the width and height properties of each cell to 100px
For testing purposes, set the background-color property to blue

.cell {
    height: 100px;
    width: 100px;
    background-color: blue;
}

Aligning the cells
Currently, each cell div will stack vertically. This is the default behavior for HTML div elements. Instead, the "cell" elements should display horizontally within each row. CSS Grid layout allows this style.

Resource: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/CSS_Grid_Layout/Basic_Concepts_of_Grid_Layout


In the CSS file, create a new ruleset for each row
Selector: .horizontal
Curly brackets


Set the display property of each row to grid
This tells the webpage that each row will have the grid layout


Set the grid-template-columns property of each row to 1fr 1fr 1fr 1fr
This will determine the number of columns in each row
The 4 1fr mean that there are 4 columns, each taking one fraction of the available width


Remove the width from the .cell ruleset as it is no longer necessary

.horizontal {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr 1fr 1fr;
}

.cell {
    height: 100px;
    background-color: blue;
}

Now, the entire main container should be blue, because each cell is 100x100 and they stack properly!
Filling out the grid with colors

In the HTML file, add a class of "black" to each black cell
Add a class of "yellow" to each yellow cell
Note that the div will now have two classes: cell and yellow
Two classes can be set with a space between them: class="cell yellow"


In the CSS file, remove the blue background-color from the "cell" elements
Create a new ruleset for "black" cells
Selector: .black


In the .black ruleset, set the background color to black
Create a new ruleset for "yellow" cells
Selector: .yellow


In the .yellow ruleset, set the background color to gold

That's it! Refresh the page and PAC-MAN should appear in the grid.
Pixels.html


































Pixels.css
#main {
    width: 400px;
    height: 400px;
    border: 2px solid black;
}

.horizontal {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr 1fr 1fr;
}

.cell {
    height: 100px;
}

.black {
    background-color: black;
}

.yellow {
    background-color: gold;
}

